-- PRESS DIGEST -Hong Kong - Aug 19
-- By Donny Kwok
-- Mon Aug 18, 2014 09:57PM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, Aug 19 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Tuesday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST  -- Beijing's top man in Hong Kong told pan-democrats their meetings with central government representatives had not come too late to shape its decision on the city's political reform, a lawmaker said. (http://bit.ly/1sQwrBm)   -- Analysts are taking a less-optimistic view of Hong Kong's economic prospects in the second half of this year after the government lowered its forecasts from 3 to 4 percent to between 2 and 3 percent. RBS and Citi analysts have lowered their full-year forecast by 0.6 percent from their previous projections, to 2.4 percent. (http://bit.ly/1tbF4ox) -- Kerry Logistics Network <0636.HK> is looking to expand in mainland China and Southeast Asia after reporting an 8 per cent rise in core net profit to HK$490 million ($63.2 million) for the first half. (http://bit.ly/1rPPozF)  THE STANDARD -- Hong Kong actor Jaycee Chan Jo-ming, son of kung fu superstar Jackie Chan Kong-sang, and a Taiwanese actor have been arrested in Beijing for alleged consumption of drugs. The pair's detention follows the announcement last week that 42 entertainment and performance agencies had stuck an agreement to boycott celebrities who take drugs. (http://bit.ly/1pC0YQu) -- JPMorgan Asset Management is of the view the Shanghai-Hong Kong Stock Connect will boost A shares more than Hong Kong stocks. Lilian Leung, fund manager of JPMorgan China A-Share Opportunities, said Hong Kong is already an open market while the mainland market is relatively shut. (http://bit.ly/1le7o8W)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  -- The Link REIT <0823.HK> has bought Lions Rise Mall in Kowloon's Wong Tai Sin for HK$1.38 billion ($178 million) from Kerry Properties <0683.HK>, its third and the biggest acquisition since listing.   MING PAO DAILY NEWS  -- Van booking service firm GoGo Van's turnover has exceeded HK$120 million ($15.5 million) since it was established about a year ago, and has lured an aggregate investment of $10 million from investors, including Centurion Private Equity. The Hong Kong firm is looking to expand into south east Asia, according to its senior management. -- Organisers of Sunday's march against Occupy Central have spent less than HK$10 million ($1.29 million) in total on the event with the funds being donated by various groups, according to Robert Chow, the spokesman for the Alliance for Peace and Democracy. For Chinese newspapers, see...............[PRESS/CN]   (1 US dollar = 7.7504 Hong Kong dollar)